OL,3,CAccidental drowning deaths likely to
OL,4,Cincrease during hot weather, says study
OL,6,FThe data in the Bournemouth University
OL,7,Fstudy suggests that when average
OL,8,Fmaximum air temperatures reach or
OL,9,Fexceed 25C, there is a fivefold
OL,10,Fincrease in accidental drowning risk
OL,11,Fwhen compared to days with an average
OL,12,Fof 10C.
OL,14,FThe RLSS UK's analysis highlights the
OL,15,Frisk of taking a swim to cool off.
OL,17,FA total of 57% of people who
OL,18,Faccidentally drowned on days exceeding
OL,19,Ftemperatures of 25C were swimming. In
OL,20,Fnormal air temperatures, 20% of
OL,21,Faccidental drownings are from swimming.
